reviewText: I've been catching up on this show for the last few weeks and have noticed that the video pixellates every now and then.  Quite often, actually.  I did a little investigating and discovered the discs are DVD-5s instead of the standard DVD-9s.  This means that they are about the same quality as DVD-Rs.  They say on the pacakaging that they are dual layered discs, but clearly they are not.  They are cramming the same amount of data as a normal DVD onto half as much space. A normal DVD (DVD-9) will contain about 7.5GB of information.  These DVDs (DVD-5) contain about 4.5GB. Just like DVD-Rs.  This means they are over compressed and a lot of data is lost.  They are a rip off plain and simple.  I don't know if all of these sets were produced this way or not, or if I was just one of the unlucky ones who got a bad set. I hope seasons seven and eight weren't released on similar discs.
summary: Still love the show - the DVDs are the problem

reviewText: I enjoyed the first 5 seasons of CSI: NY, but season 6 was disappointing and confusing.The back stories for the major characters were either obvious or went nowhere. The opening storyline, dealing with whether Danny will walk again, ends with the predictable resolution and is played like a soppy extended episode of "Touch by an Angel."Then there's this whole storyline of a female intern after Adam's job that disappears after Episode 6.Also disappearing for about 6 episodes with no explanation is Anna Belknap's Lindsey character.Another possible storyline, in which Dr. Sheldon Hawkes is broke and moves in with Mac Taylor, ends with one line of dialogue in the next episode.Toward the end of Season 6, the producers gave Mac Taylor a new girlfriend, but she really has nothing to do with any of the cases and isn't even in the final episode.Even that final episode is disappointing. It uses a hackneyed, trite soap opera convention, which had me screaming at my TV monitor, to set up a cliffhanger.Many of the cases this season seemed run-of-the-mill to me, but I do have to applaud the "Rear Window"-like episode. It expertly took the Hitchcock movie and added CSI touches.

reviewText: Let me start by stating that I do like CSI:NY and I own all six seasons of the show.  However, if I had seen the show first, then I would not have bought the sixth season.  Here are my reasons:1.  They might as well as change the name of the show to Mac Taylor Show, since he does everything (everything but the science stuff).  He interviews all suspects, he orders everyone around to include the captain, chases all bad guys and catches all bad guys.  No police needed when Mac is on the case.2.  There is a lot less science stuff (this is compared to CSI: LV).  They do talk a lot of science, but nothing visual.  Most of the time, they discuss the science stuff with (who else) Mac, but that is where it ends.  However, there is a lot of interviewing going on, but I liked it when they discover stuff via physical investigation.  If I want interviews, then I could always watch Law&Order; or Cold Case.3.  They are trying too hard to dramatize the show.  Since Mac has taken over the show, there is not a lot time for other actors to shine.  (A case in point is the new girl who had the potential to be a good addition to the team, but taken away after a couple of shows.  If they got no time for old timers, then they certainly don't have enough time for a new character.)  However, in order to get other actors involved, they get one shining moment, such as, Sid's case with dead football girl, Danny with his wheelchair issue, Doc with his money problem, Flak with his drinking issue.  All was interesting, but never really developed.  These were brought up and solved with no impact to the show (of course Mac was the man for these issues).I do recommend this show (good cases), but I don't know about buying it.  I would stick with CSI:LV (even without Grissom, they did a fantastic job.  You gotta love the interaction between the actors and gotta love Jim Brass.)  So, enjoy and hope this helped.
summary: A little disappointed compared to previous seasons

reviewText: Now that the new season with the new cast has passed we are able to see reruns of the older seasons of CSI:NY, and fond memories of this initial team of actors and their ability to interface and make so many memorable moments is again something to appreciated.  Not that the new cast with Sela Ward is drastically different, but many of us miss the chemistry that Melina Kanakaredes brought to the team.  This cast - the durable Gary Sinise, Carmine Giovinazzo, Hill Harper, Eddie Cahill (why doesn't this actor get to make more movies?), Anna Belknap, Robert Joy, and A.J. Buckley seemed to have the combined intensity of a team who could solve everything smoothly, introducing the audience to the latest techniques of forensic medicine, and yet manage to provide sufficient camaraderie to make them all seem like good friends.  Great writing, fine acting, sustainable solid series.  Grady Harp, September 12
summary: Better with Age, Like a Fine Wine!

reviewText: This should have been excellent, I certainly expected to sit down and enjoy my evenings with Mac Taylor and his team. I have been surprised to find that this series of CSI has even exceeded the other two - certainly left the original Las Vegas one lagging a long way behind - and I waited a long time for season six.  What a horror!!!!  I assume these DVD's are put out by CBS and I have to state that they need to pay real attention to what is being replicated for the paying public. I have had THREE copies of this season and all three have appalling sound problems - to the extent where it completely spoils my enjoyment. Please CBS DO something about this. I am waiting with trepidation for season 7 - will it be as bad? I hope not - I do not want my love affair with Mac to come to such an ignominious end!

They bring into the series a greater depth in the relationships of the main characters. Enjoy it, buy it, I did, twice (lost the first copy to Hurricane Sandy).And tell em' you've read another great review byRalph J. Fitcher.

reviewText: The Sixth Season of CSI:NY returns with Gary Sinise, Hill Harper, Carmine Giovanazzo, Eddie Cahill, Anna Belknap, Robert Joy, A.J Buckley, and after six seasons, 141 episodes, Melina Kanakaredes returns in her final season of the show as CSI Stella Bonasera. In the sixth season of CSI:NY contains a bonus crossover episodes of CSI:Las Vegas, and CSI:Miami joining forces for the first time. The first story starts off with CSI:Miami, the second story continues with CSI:NY, and it concludes on CSI:Las Vegas. All of the three CSI franchises is one of the best franchises in the history of television!!
